---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Heidegger: Authenticity, Resoluteness, and Being-towards-Death | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Heidegger</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Authenticity, Resoluteness, and Being-towards-Death
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					The ontological analysis of Dasein and the call to authentic existence: owning one’s thrownness and projecting resolutely in the face of finitude.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong>
					First Heidegger in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering.
					Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Dasein and the Structure of Existence</div>
					<p>
						In *Being and Time* (1927) Martin Heidegger analyzes human existence as **Dasein** — Being-there. Dasein is not a thing among things but the kind of being that understands Being, is always already in a world, and has possibilities.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Dasein is characterized by **thrownness** (Geworfenheit): we are always already thrown into a situation, a mood, a historical context that we did not choose. At the same time, Dasein is always projecting itself forward into possibilities.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Authenticity, the They, and Being-towards-Death</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core distinction (Heidegger):</strong> Inauthentic Dasein loses itself in “the they” (das Man) — everyday idle talk, curiosity, and ambiguity. Authentic Dasein hears the call of conscience, faces its own finitude (Being-towards-death), and resolutely takes over its thrownness.
					</div>
					<p>
						Being-towards-death is not a morbid preoccupation but the horizon that makes existence urgent and meaningful. Death is the ultimate possibility that cannot be outstripped; facing it individuates Dasein and calls it back from absorption in the they.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Resoluteness (Entschlossenheit) is the authentic mode in which Dasein owns its situation and projects its possibilities with clarity and commitment.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Heidegger:</strong> existence is always already situated (thrown) yet open to authentic projection. Identity is not a neutral bundle or pure freedom but a structure of care, finitude, and resolute choice.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> thrownness as the given starting geometry of the Stem; resoluteness as high-Mass, committed curvature; Being-towards-death as the horizon that gives urgency to maximizing meaningful causal futures; and authenticity as owning one’s identity geometry instead of drifting in default social structures.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Thrownness + Projection:</strong> We are always already in a situation with a certain identity geometry (thrownness). Authentic existence means resolutely taking this over and projecting forward with clarity — exactly the movement from given Stem to deliberate curvature.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">The They as low-Mass default:</strong> Absorption in everydayness and social roles is the inauthentic mode that keeps identity diffuse, low-Mass, and uncurved by personal resoluteness. It reduces causal entropy by surrendering to the average.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Being-towards-death as horizon:</strong> Facing finitude makes choices urgent and meaningful. It is the ultimate test for whether one’s identity geometry is oriented toward open, significant futures or toward evasion and dispersion.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Resoluteness as committed curvature:</strong> Resoluteness is the existential equivalent of adding high Mass and deliberately curving one’s identity geometry in a chosen direction with full ownership.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Heidegger provides an ontological and phenomenological depth that complements Sartre’s radical freedom. While Sartre emphasizes absolute choice and responsibility, Heidegger shows the structures within which choice always already operates (thrownness, care, Being-towards-death). He adds the dimension of finitude and resoluteness as the authentic mode of owning one’s identity geometry. Compared to Jung, Heidegger is less focused on unconscious contents and more on the ontological structures of existence and authentic projection.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: Martin Heidegger, <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Being and Time</em> (1927), especially Division I on Dasein and Division II on authenticity and Being-towards-death.
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/heidegger/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Heidegger</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Heidegger is the major ontological voice in the modern sequence. He deepens the existential analysis by showing the structures of thrownness, care, and finitude within which freedom and choice always operate. This anchor adds the dimension of authentic resoluteness and Being-towards-death as the horizon that gives urgency and meaning to identity design.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
